Rachel Jones's post 2w ago:
The first 2025 National Press Foundation  Widening the Pipeline virtual training wrapped on Monday. Three sessions focused on covering immigration and immigrant communities, with exceptional journalists providing deep insights and solid reporting tips for the fellows.

So grateful to our speakers:

*Martina Guzman, Director of Community Journalism at Planet Detroit where she leads the Neighborhood Reporting Lab and mentors residents to tell community stories. Martina developed the Verdad app that helps journalists identify mis/disinformation on Spanish language radio;

*Emma Cordover, a Digital Producer with POLITICO who produced an intriguing Women Rule newsletter about how Trump’s executive orders about immigration are affecting maternal health;

*Tandy Lau, one of the first Asian American reporters for the New York Amsterdam News, one of the nation’s oldest Black newspapers. Tandy covers public safety for the Amsterdam News, and advised fellows about the challenges for people confronting the fast evolving landscape of immigration policy.

The #NPFWidening secret formula relies on smart, committed journalists who generously support our mission of making good journalists better. Monday’s virtual training launch was a solid sign of great things to come.

Rachel Jones's post 1mo ago:
The launch of the 2025 National Press Foundation Widening the Pipeline fellowship could not have rolled out better if I’d waved a magic wand! The energy and enthusiasm of the 20 early career journalists of color participants was matched by the potent insights and enormous generosity of spirit from stellar speakers who spoke truth and light to the fellows.

* Sending gratitude and thanks to the Remarkable Ms. Kelsey Russell, that magnetic young media influencer who taught us all about the opportunities that exist at the intersection of audience engagement, social media and journalism;

* The ever inspiring Catalina Camia of Bloomberg Law, whose dedication to mentoring and supporting journalists helped create the Widening the Pipeline program; 

* 2024 Widening fellow Bianca Quilantan  of POLITICO who shared profound insights about personal career challenges and the invigorating mentorship she received from Catalina Camia;

* And last but most definitely not least, the inimitable Torrance Latham  of the Miami Herald, an original #NPFWidening fellow whose dynamic vision is a literal fountain of motivation and peer support. 

I’ve already said it about a hundred times, so once more won’t hurt. My work with journalists in the National Press Foundation Widening the Pipeline program is the great privilege of this golden era of my life and career. Their journeys give me hope and inspiration to, as my mother Eloise used to say, “Keep on keepin’ on”!
